      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Oh, managing a clothing boutique? That's a lot of work, but honestly, it's a lot of work that could be a lot more efficient if you just had a few goblins to help you out. You know, the little green things with the pointy ears and the endless pockets full of shiny trinkets? They're actually pretty good at organizing things, though they do tend to get distracted by shiny new fabrics.\n\nAnyway, back to your efficiency question. To calculate your **inventory turnover ratio**, you simply take your **Cost of Goods Sold (COGS)** and divide it by your **Average Inventory**.\n\nHere's the formula:\n$$ \\text{Inventory Turnover} = \\frac{\\text{Cost of Goods Sold}}{\\text{Average Inventory}} $$\n\nThe \"Average Inventory\" is usually calculated by taking the beginning inventory plus the ending inventory and dividing by two. It's like counting how many goblins you have at the start of the week and how many you have at the end, then averaging it out to see how many are working on the floor versus hiding in the back.\n\nNow, regarding your question about what a **low** number means: A low inventory turnover ratio generally indicates that your",
